and keeping it in an ice-hou&s;e, he delayed it, viii. 26&mdash;the ef|forts
which it makes to get free from its aurelia &s;tate, are not &s;o violent as
tho&s;e had in changing from the caterpillar into the aurelia, viii.
27&mdash;how the butterfly gets rid of the aurelia, viii. 28&mdash;ea&s;ily
di&s;tin|gui&s;hed from flies of every other kind by their wings&mdash;Linnaeus
has reckoned up above &s;even hundred and &s;ixty different kinds, yet the
catalogue is incomplete, viii. 32&mdash;number and beautiful colours of its
wings, viii. 33&mdash;butterflies can di&s;cover their mates at more than a
mile's di&s;tance, viii. 34&mdash;de&s;cription of the head, cor&s;elet, and
body, viii. 35&mdash;the eyes have not all the &s;ame form; but the outward
coat has a lu&s;tre, in which may be di&s;covered all the colours of the
rainbow&mdash;when examined clo&s;ely, it has the appearance of a multiplying
gla&s;s, viii. 36&mdash;the u&s;e of their horns or feelers as yet unknown,
viii. 37&mdash;u&s;e of their trunks&mdash;difference between butterflies and
moths, viii. 38&mdash;they often perceive the ap|proach of the female at above
two miles di&s;tance; by what &s;en&s;e is not ea&s;y to conceive&mdash;it has
no organs for &s;melling&mdash;the female is larger than the male, viii.
39&mdash;if di&s;turbed while united, the fe|male flies off with the male on
her back, entirely pa&s;&s;ive upon the occa&s;ion&mdash;after junction, they
de|po&s;ite their eggs and die&mdash;all females of this tribe are impregnated
by the male by one aperture, and lay their eggs by another, viii.
40&mdash;every butterfly chu&s;es for her brood, in&s;tead of the plant mo&s;t
grateful in its winged &s;tate, that it has fed upon in its reptile
form&mdash;how they keep their eggs warm, and al&s;o entirely concealed, viii.
41&mdash;many do not lay till the winter warns them of their approaching end;
&s;ome continue the whole winter in hollows of trees, and do not provide for
