<ITEM><HI>Eagle kind,</HI> di&s;tinctive marks from the other kinds
of carnivorous birds, v. 85&mdash;the golden eagle is the large&s;t and the
noble&s;t of all tho&s;e birds de&s;igned by the name of eagle, v. 87&mdash;its
de&s;cription&mdash;con|&s;idered among birds, as the lion among quadru|peds,
v. 87, 88&mdash;&s;trong &s;imilitude to each other&mdash;great patience, and
much art, required to tame an eagle; though taken young, and brought under by
long a&s;&s;iduity, yet it is a dangerous dome&s;tic, and often turns its force
again&s;t its ma&s;ter, v. 89&mdash;&s;ometimes has an attachment for its
feeder; it is then &s;erviceable, and will provide for his plea&s;ures and
&s;upport&mdash;flies the highe&s;t of all birds, and from thence has by the
ancients been called the bird of heaven&mdash;it has al&s;o the quicke&s;t eye;
but its &s;en&s;e of &s;melling is far inferior to that of the vulture&mdash;it
never pur&s;ues, but in &s;ight, v. 90&mdash;finds difficulty in ri&s;ing when
down&mdash;carries a|way gee&s;e, cranes, hares, lambs, and kids, and often
de&s;troys fawns and calves, to drink their blood, and carries a part of their
fle&s;h to its re|treats&mdash;infants, when left unattended, have been
de&s;troyed by the&s;e rapacious creatures&mdash;the eagle is peculiarly
formidable when bringing up its young&mdash;a poor man got a comfortable
&s;ub&s;i&s;tence for his family, during a &s;ummer of famine, out of an
eagle's ne&s;t, by robbing the eaglets of food, v. 91&mdash;eagles killed a
pea&s;ant who had robbed their ne&s;ts&mdash;there is a law in the Orkney
i&s;lands, which entitles any per&s;on that kills an eagle to a hen out of
every hou&s;e in the pari&s;h, in which the plunderer is killed&mdash;the
ne&s;t of the eagle is u&s;ually built in the mo&s;t inacce&s;&s;ible cliff of
the rock, v. 92&mdash;de&s;cription of one found in the Peak of
Derby&s;hire&mdash;it hatches its eggs for thirty days&mdash;very rare to find
three eaglets in the <PB REF="297"> &s;ame ne&s;t; and it is a&s;&s;erted, that
the mother kills the mo&s;t feeble, or the mo&s;t voracious, v. 93, 94&mdash;it
is believed they live above an hundred years, and that they die, not of old
age, but from the beaks turning inward upon the under jaw, and preventing their
taking any food&mdash;an eagle en|dured hunger for twenty-one days, without any
&s;u&s;tenance whatever&mdash;they are fir&s;t white, then in|clining to
yellow, and at la&s;t light brown, v. 94&mdash;age, hunger, captivity, and
di&s;ea&s;es, make them whiter&mdash;tho&s;e kept tame are fed with every kind
of fle&s;h, fre&s;h or corrupting; and upon a deficiency of that, bread, or any
other provi&s;ion, will &s;uffice&mdash;it is dangerous approaching them, if
not quite tame; and they &s;ometimes &s;end forth a loud piercing la|mentable
cry, which renders them &s;till more for|midable&mdash;they drink but &s;eldom,
and perhaps when at liberty, not at all, v. 95&mdash;the bald eagle an
inha|bitant of North Carolina&mdash;breeds in that country all the year
round&mdash;manner in which the eggs are hatched&mdash;characteri&s;tics and
habitudes of this ani|mal&mdash;its ne&s;t is large enough to fill the body of
a cart, and commonly full of bones half eaten, and putrid fle&s;h, the &s;tench
of which is intolerable, v. 96&mdash;the flap of an eagle's wing known to lay a
man dead in an in&s;tant, v. 9&mdash;it flies at the bu&s;|tard or the
phea&s;ant, v. 81</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Eagle,</HI> the <HI>&s;ea-eagle</HI> called <HI>aquila
piombina</HI> by the Ita|lians, v. 95&mdash;they often lay three or four eggs,
of a le&s;s &s;ize than tho&s;e of a hen, of a white eliptical
form&mdash;di&s;tinctive marks of the <HI>golden eagle,</HI> of the <HI>common
