de&s;cription of each mu&s;t be u&s;ele&s;s and tire&s;ome, their numbers being
very great, and their differences very trifling&mdash;tho&s;e of two cantons
never found to mix&mdash;of all kinds le&s;s than the baboon, have le&s;s power
of do|ing mi&s;chief, and their ferocity dimini&s;hes with their &s;ize, iv.
217, 218&mdash;do nothing de&s;ired without beating; their fears once removed,
they are the mo&s;t in&s;olent head&s;trong animals in nature&mdash;in their
native woods, are the pe&s;ts of other ani|mals, and the ma&s;ters of the
fore&s;t where they re|&s;ide&mdash;the tiger, nor the lion will not venture to
di&s;|pute dominion with creatures, who from the tops of trees with impunity
