ap|petite to devour them, iv. 219&mdash;one only animal in the fore&s;t
ventures to oppo&s;e them, that is the &s;erpent&mdash;larger &s;nakes often
wind up the trees where they re&s;ide, and happening to &s;urprize them
&s;leeping, &s;wallow them whole, before they can make defence&mdash;they
generally inhabit the tops of trees, and the &s;nakes cling to the branches
nearer the bottom, in this manner they are near each o|ther, like enemies in
the &s;ame field of battle&mdash;&s;ome &s;uppo&s;ed their vicinity rather
argued mutual friend|&s;hip&mdash;father Labat has &s;een them playing their
gambols upon tho&s;e branches on which the &s;nakes <PB REF="402"> were
repo&s;ing, and jumping over them without re|ceiving any injury, iv.
220&mdash;they provoke the &s;nake as the &s;parrows twitter at a
cat&mdash;when attacked, they &s;how perfect &s;kill in defending and
a&s;&s;i&s;ting each other&mdash;they regularly begin ho&s;tilities again&s;t
tho&s;e who enter their woods, iv. 221&mdash;they take mo&s;t de&s;perate
leaps, and &s;eldom come to the ground&mdash;one being wounded, the re&s;t come
round, put their fingers into the wound, as de|&s;irous of &s;ounding its
depth&mdash;the blood flowing in any quantity, &s;ome &s;top it, while others
get leaves, chew, and thru&s;t them into the opening&mdash;are often killed in
numbers before they make a retreat, with the &s;ame precipitation as they at
fir&s;t came on&mdash;in this retreat the young are clinging to the back of the
female, who jumps away, &s;eem|ingly unembarra&s;&s;ed by the burthen, iv.
222&mdash;u&s;ual way of taking them alive&mdash;the monkey not killed
outright, does not fall; but clinging to &s;ome branch, continues, when dead,
its la&s;t gra&s;p, and remains where &s;hot, until it drops by putrefaction,
iv. 223&mdash;&s;kinned and &s;erved up at negroe-fea&s;ts, &s;o like a child,
an European is &s;hocked at the &s;ight, iv. 224&mdash;the negroes &s;eeing
Europeans buy young and tame monkies, with equal care brought rats to the
factors for &s;ale, and were greatly di&s;appointed find|ing no
purcha&s;er&mdash;negroes cannot comprehend ad|vantages ari&s;ing from
educating or keeping animals who come in companies to lay wa&s;te fields of
corn or rice, or plantations of &s;ugar-canes&mdash;they carry off what they
are able, and de&s;troy ten times more, iv. 224, 225&mdash;manner of their
plundering&mdash;are un|der a kind of di&s;cipline, exerci&s;ed among
them&s;elves, iv. 225&mdash;account to this purpo&s;e by Morgrave&mdash;one
&s;pecies, by Mr. Buffon called the ouarine, remarkable for loudne&s;s and
di&s;tinctne&s;s of voice&mdash;u&s;e to which they convert it&mdash;are
generally together in com|panies, march in exact order, and obey the voice of
&s;ome chieftain, remarkable for his &s;ize and gra|vity, iv. 226&mdash;chief
food of the tribe, iv. 227&mdash;ex|traordinary <PB REF="403"> manner of
managing an oy&s;ter&mdash;manner of drawing crabs from the water,&mdash;no
&s;nare, how nicely baited, takes a monkey of the We&s;t Indian
i&s;lands&mdash;female brings forth one, and &s;ometimes two at a
time&mdash;rarely breed when brought into Europe&mdash;the male and female
never tired of fondling their young, and in|&s;truct it with no little
a&s;&s;iduity&mdash;often &s;everely cor|rect it, if &s;tubborn, or
di&s;inclined to profit by their example&mdash;manner of carrying their young
in the woods, iv. 227, 228&mdash;dexterity in pa&s;&s;ing from one tree to
another, by forming a kind of chain, lock|ing tail in tail, or hand in hand,
iv. 229&mdash;one amu&s;ed it&s;elf for hours impo&s;ing upon the gravity of a
cat&mdash;and playing its pranks among rabbits, iv. 230&mdash;faithful
&s;ervices which father Carli received from the monkies in Angola, where he
went to convert the &s;avage natives to Chri&s;tianity&mdash;&s;avages of
Africa and America, &s;uppo&s;e monkies to be men; idle, &s;lothful, ra|tional
beings, capable of &s;peech and conver&s;a- but ob&s;tinately dumb, for fear of
being compelled to labour&mdash;monkies of Africa mo&s;t expert and
entertaining, iv. 231&mdash;&s;hew a greater degree of cunning and
activity&mdash;three marks by which mon|kies of the new continent are
di&s;tingui&s;hed from tho&s;e of the old, iv. 232&mdash;Mr. Buffon makes but
nine &s;pecies of monkies belonging to the ancient continent, and eleven to the
new&mdash;their names, with their de&s;criptions, iv. 232 to 238&mdash;the
<HI>red African,</HI> the <HI>patas,</HI> &s;econd &s;ort of the ancient
con|tinent, iv. 233&mdash;the <HI>white no&s;e,</HI> or <HI>mou&s;toc,</HI> of
the ancient continent, mo&s;t beautiful, its de&s;cription&mdash;the
<HI>green</HI> of St. Jago, al&s;o called <HI>callitrix,</HI> is of the ancient
continent&mdash;its de&s;cription, iv. 234&mdash;&s;ome of the kinds eat their
own tail, and &s;eem to feel no pain, iv. 336&mdash;the Bramins have
ho&s;pitals for tho&s;e that happen to be &s;ick, or di&s;abled, iv.
234&mdash;tho&s;e monkies of the new continent with mu&s;cular holding tails,
