mu&s;ic; and where they have not &s;kill to produce harmony, they
&s;ub&s;titute noi&s;e, ii. 167&mdash;its effects, the ancients give us many
&s;trange in&s;tances of them upon men and ani|mals, <PB REF="409"> ii.
168&mdash;and the moderns likewi&s;e, ii. 169&mdash;madne&s;s cured by
it&mdash;and al&s;o excited by it&mdash;re|markable in&s;tance in Henry IV. of
Denmark, ii. 170&mdash;it is now well known that the &s;tories of the bite of
