likewi&s;e, ii. 168, 169&mdash;the elephant appears delighted with mu&s;ic, iv.
258&mdash;father Kircher has &s;et the voices of birds to mu&s;ic, v.
143</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Mu&s;k,</HI> a doubt whether the animal producing it be a
hog, an ox, a goat, or a deer, iii. 89&mdash;no animal &s;o ju&s;tly the
reproach of natural hi&s;torians as that which bears the mu&s;k, iii.
88&mdash;it has been variou&s;ly de&s;cribed, and is known very imperfectly,
iii. 90&mdash;the de&s;cription given by Grew, iii. 90, 91&mdash;among the
numerous medicines procurable from quadrupeds, none, except the mu&s;k and
harts-horn, have pre&s;erved a degree of reputation, iii. 69&mdash;formerly in
high reque&s;t as a perfume, iii. 93&mdash;has for more than a century been
imported from the Ea&s;t, iii. 88&mdash;is a du&s;ky reddi&s;h &s;ub&s;tance,
