191&mdash;gigantic races of it de&s;cribed by travellers truly
formidable&mdash;many are taller than man, active, &s;trong, intrepid, cunning,
la&s;civious, and cruel&mdash;countries where found&mdash;in Borneo the
qua|lity cour&s;e him as we do the &s;tag, and this hunting is a favourite
amu&s;ement of the king&mdash;runs with great celerity&mdash;its de&s;cription,
iv. 200 to 202&mdash;Battel calls him pongo; a&s;&s;ures us that in all he
re&s;embles man, but is larger to a gigantic &s;tate&mdash;a native of the
tropical climates&mdash;he lives upon fruits, and is not carnivorous&mdash;goes
in companies; and this troop meeting one of the human &s;pecies without
&s;uccour, &s;hew him no mercy&mdash;they jointly attack the ele|phant, beat
him with clubs, and force him to leave that part of the fore&s;t they claim as
their own, iv. 201&mdash;is &s;o &s;trong, that ten men are not a match 
<PB REF="422"> for it&mdash;none of the kind taken but very young&mdash;one of
them dying, the re&s;t cover the body with leaves and branches&mdash;a negro
boy taken by one of the&s;e, and carried into the woods, con|tinued there a
whole year without any injury&mdash;they often attempt the female negroes going
into the woods, and keep them again&s;t their wills for their company, feeding
them plentifully all the time&mdash;a traveller a&s;&s;ures, that he knew a
woman of Loango that lived among them for three years&mdash;they build &s;heds,
and u&s;e clubs for their defence, iv. 202&mdash;&s;ometimes walk upright, and
&s;ometimes upon all fours, when phanta&s;tically di&s;po&s;ed, iv.
203&mdash;tho' it re&s;embles man in form, and imitates his actions, it is
inferior in &s;agacity even to the elephant or the beaver, iv. 204&mdash;two of
