them&mdash;the Greeks were &s;o much taken with the beauty of this bird, when
fir&s;t brought among them, that it was &s;hewn for money; and many came to
A|thens from Lacedaemon and The&s;&s;aly to &s;ee it, v. 172&mdash;once
e&s;teemed a delicacy at the tables of the rich and great, v.
171&mdash;Au&s;idius Hurco &s;tands charged by Pliny with being the fir&s;t who
fatted up the pea|cock for the fea&s;ts of the luxurious, v.
172&mdash;Hor|ten&s;ius the orator was the fir&s;t who &s;erved them up at an
entertainment at Rome&mdash;and they are talked of as the fir&s;t of
viands&mdash;in the times of Francis I. it was a cu&s;tom to &s;erve up
peacocks to the tables of the great, not to be eaten, but &s;een; in what
manner they &s;erved them&mdash;its fle&s;h is &s;aid to keep longer
unputrefied than any other, v. 173&mdash;has a predilection for
barley&mdash;but as a proud and fickle bird, there is &s;carce any food it will
at all times like&mdash;it &s;trips the tops of hou&s;es of tiles or thatch,
lays wa&s;te the labours of the garden|er, roots up the choice&s;t &s;eeds, and
nips favourite flowers in the bud&mdash;is &s;till more &s;alacious than the
