de&s;cription&mdash;has upon the back a lump like the navel in other animals,
iii. 183&mdash;it con&s;i&s;ts of glands producing a liquor of an offen&s;ive
&s;mell, iii. 184&mdash;when killed the parts of generation and the glands on
the back mu&s;t be taken in&s;tantly away, otherwi&s;e in half an hour the
fle&s;h becomes unfit to be eaten, iii. 186&mdash;though like the hog in many
re&s;pects, is never|thele&s;s a di&s;tinct race, and will not mix nor pro|duce
an intermediate race&mdash;is ea&s;ily tamed, iii. 188&mdash;goes in herds of
two or three hundred, and unites, like hogs, in each other's defence, iii.
186&mdash;delights not in mar&s;hes or mud like our hogs&mdash;an uncea&s;ing
enemy to the lizard, the toad, and the &s;erpent kinds&mdash;al&s;o feeds upon
toads and &s;er|pents, iii. 187&mdash;any plunderer &s;eizing their young is
&s;urrounded and often killed, iii. 186</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pedigree,</HI> the Arabians pre&s;erve that of their
be&s;t hor&s;es with great care, and for &s;everal generations back, ii.
350</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pegu,</HI> a river called the Indian Nile, becau&s;e of
the &s;imilar overflowings of its &s;tream, i. 218</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pelagii,</HI> the Latin name for tho&s;e &s;hells
fi&s;hed up from the deep&mdash;tho&s;e ca&s;t on the &s;hore are the
littorales, vii. 13</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pelican,</HI> a ruminating bird, iii. 5&mdash;a native of
Africa and America; once known in Europe, particular|ly in
Ru&s;&s;ia&mdash;fabulous accounts propagated of it&mdash;the de&s;cription of
it, particularly of its bill, and the great pouch underneath, as
wonderful&mdash;Tertre af|firms the pouch will hide fi&s;h enough to &s;erve
&s;ixty hungry men for a meal&mdash;this pouch placed at the top of the gullet,
con&s;idered as the crop in other birds, vi. 51 to 53&mdash;the de&s;cription
of the bird from <PB REF="435"> father Labat, vi. 54&mdash;indolent habits in
preparing for incubation, and defending their young, vi. 56&mdash;their
gluttony &s;carcely to be &s;atisfied; their fle&s;h rancid, and ta&s;tes
wor&s;e than it &s;mells&mdash;u&s;e made by the Americans of their pouches,
vi. 57&mdash;is not entirely incapable of in&s;truction in a dome&s;tic
&s;tate&mdash;in&s;tances of it, vi. 58&mdash;Aldrovandus mentions one believed
to be fifty years old, vi. 59</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Penguin,</HI> a heavy water fowl; the wings of this tribe
unfit for flight, vi. 90&mdash;and their legs &s;till more auk|wardly adapted
for walking, vi. 91&mdash;our &s;ailors call them ar&s;e-feet&mdash;they dive
to the bottom, or &s;wim between two waters&mdash;they never vi&s;it land but
when coming to breed, vi. 92&mdash;their colour&mdash;are covered more warmly
with feathers than other birds&mdash;de|&s;cription of the Magellanic penguin,
vi. 93&mdash;they unite in them the qualities of men, fowls, and
fi&s;hes&mdash;in&s;tances of its gluttonous appetite&mdash;their food and
fle&s;h&mdash;are a bird of &s;ociety, vi. 94&mdash;&s;ea&s;on of laying, and
manner of making their ne&s;ts, vi. 95&mdash;&s;ome of this tribe called by our
&s;eamen the booby&mdash;our men fir&s;t coming among them, were not
di&s;tru&s;ted nor avoided, they &s;tood to be &s;hot at in flocks, till every
one was de&s;troyed&mdash;the females let them take their eggs without any
re&s;i&s;tance, vi. 96&mdash;the penguin lays but one egg; in frequented
&s;hores&mdash;burrows like a rabbit&mdash;three or four take
po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of one hole, and hatch&mdash;one is placed as a centinel to
warn of approaching danger, vi. 97&mdash;union between this bird and the
albatro&s;s, and regularity in their building together, vi. 63</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Penin&s;ula</HI> of India, on one &s;ide the coa&s;ts are
near half the year harra&s;&s;ed by violent hurricanes and north|ern
tempe&s;ts, i. 348&mdash;the people there employ the elephant chiefly in
carrying or drawing burthens, iv. 278</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Penpark-hole,</HI> in Glouce&s;ter&s;hire, twenty-five
fathom perpendicular depth&mdash;its de&s;cription, from captain Sturmey, i.
66</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB REF="436"><HI>People,</HI> &s;o young as fourteen or
fifteen often found to cea&s;e growing, ii. 19</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pepper,</HI> the Indians prefer that devoured and voided
unconcocted by the toucan, before the pepper fre&s;h gathered from the tree, v.
244</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Perch,</HI> a prickly-finned thoracic fi&s;h&mdash;its
de&s;cription, vi. 308</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Perfumes,</HI> &s;ome phy&s;icians think all perfumes
un|whole&s;ome&mdash;our delight in perfumes &s;eems made by habit, ii.
181&mdash;many bodies at a di&s;tance give an agreeable perfume, and nearer
have a mo&s;t un|grateful odour, ii. 182&mdash;no perfume has a &s;trong|er or
more permanent &s;mell than mu&s;k, iii. 89&mdash;the &s;cent of the martin a
mo&s;t plea&s;ing perfume, iii. 367&mdash;&s;ome of the wea&s;el kind have a
&s;mell approach|ing to perfume, iii. 380&mdash;that of the mu&s;k or the
civet, iii. 382&mdash;in what manner taken from the pouch, iii. 391&mdash;more
grateful perfume than mu&s;k, iii. 393&mdash;that of Am&s;terdam the pure&s;t
of any,&mdash;is communicated to all parts of the animals body; the fur
impregnated, and the &s;kin al&s;o&mdash;a per&s;on &s;hut up with one of the
&s;kins in a clo&s;e room cannot &s;upport the &s;cent, iii. 192&mdash;this
perfume &s;old in Holland for about fifteen &s;hillings an ounce, iii.
393&mdash;it has no analogy with the creature's appetite for generation, iii.
395&mdash;a proof of it&mdash;has its vici&s;&s;i|tudes of fa&s;hion, like
dre&s;s, iii. 394</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;epolis,</HI> pa&s;tures in the plains about that
place ex|cellent for the purpo&s;es of rearing hor&s;es, ii. 361</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;ia</HI> &s;now falls in abundance upon its
mountains, i. 358&mdash;the hor&s;es of that country the mo&s;t beauti|ful and
mo&s;t valuable of all in the Ea&s;t, ii. 361&mdash;there are &s;tuds of ten
thou&s;and white mares toge|ther, with the hoof &s;o hard that &s;hoeing is
unnece&s;|&s;ary, ii. 355&mdash;de&s;cription of the Per&s;ian hor&s;es by
Pietro della Valle, ii. 361&mdash;the fle&s;h of the wild a&s;s &s;o much liked
that its delicacy is a proverb there, ii. 378&mdash;an entertainment of wild
a&s;&s;es ex|hibited by the monarch to Olearius, ii. 377, 378&mdash;two kinds
of a&s;&s;es there, and &s;ome of them <PB REF="437"> worth forty or fifty
pounds, ii. 385, 386&mdash;a noted country for giving long &s;oft hair to the
animals bred in it, iii. 212&mdash;lions found to dimini&s;h in number in this
country, iii. 215&mdash;the bird of Per&s;ia is the common cock of
Ari&s;tophanes, v. 161</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;ian Gulph,</HI> a very dangerous wind prevails, by
the natives called the &s;ameyel&mdash;it &s;uddenly kills tho&s;e it involves
in its pa&s;&s;age, and frequently a&s;&s;umes a vi|&s;ible form, darting in a
bluei&s;h vapour along the &s;urface of the country, i. 358&mdash;the poets of
Per|&s;ia and Arabia have de&s;cribed it as under the con|duct of vengeance,
who governs its terrors, and rai&s;es or depre&s;&s;es it, as he thinks proper,
i. 359&mdash;the chief pearl fi&s;hery carried on there, vii. 56&mdash;that
gulph choaked up in many places with cora|line &s;ub&s;tances, viii. 192</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;ian kings,</HI> wore their whi&s;kers matted with
gold thread, ii. 97</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;ians</HI> admire large eye-brows, joining in the
mid|dle, ii. 76&mdash;divided into two cla&s;&s;es, tyrants and &s;laves, vii.
58</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Per&s;piration,</HI> an experiment from which the learned
