mummy, ii. 287</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pettichaps,</HI> a bird of the &s;parrow-kind, v.
314</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Phalanger,</HI> a kind of oppo&s;&s;um&mdash;its
de&s;cription&mdash;has been called the rat of Surinam, iv. 248</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pharaoh,</HI> (the cat of) name given to the ichneumon,
iii. 376</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB REF="438"><HI>Pharaoh,</HI> (the capon of) thought to be
the true ibis&mdash;a devourer of &s;erpents, and will follow the cara|vans to
Mecca, to feed upon the offal of animals killed on the journey, v. 385</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pha&s;is,</HI> a river of Colchis, in A&s;ia Minor, from
the banks of which the phea&s;ants were brought into Europe, and &s;till retain
their name, v. 184</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Phatagin,</HI> an animal le&s;s than the
pangolin&mdash;the ex|tent of its tail above twice the length of its
body&mdash;countries where it is to be found, iv. 124</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Phea&s;ants,</HI> at fir&s;t propagated among us, brought
in|to Europe from the banks of the Pha&s;is, a river of Colchis, in A&s;ia
Minor, whence they &s;till retain their name&mdash;Croe&s;us, king of Lydia,
&s;eat|ed on his throne, adorned with the barbarous pomp of ea&s;tern
&s;plendour, a&s;ked Solon whether he ever beheld any thing &s;o fine? Solon
replied, that hav|ing &s;een the beautiful plumage of the phea&s;ant, no other
finery could a&s;toni&s;h him, v. 184&mdash;de&s;crip|tion of this beautiful
bird, v. 185&mdash;its fle&s;h the greate&s;t dainty&mdash;animals of the
dome&s;tic kind, once reclaimed, &s;till continue dome&s;tic, and per&s;evere
in the habits and appetites of willing &s;lav|ery; but the phea&s;ant, taken
from its native warm retreats, &s;till continues his attachment to native
freedom; and wild among us, is an envied orna|ment of our parks and fore&s;ts,
where he feeds upon acorns and berries, v. 186&mdash;in the woods the hen
phea&s;ant lays from eighteen to twenty eggs in a &s;ea|&s;on; but in a
dome&s;tic &s;tate &s;eldom above ten&mdash;when wild, &s;he hatches and leads
up her brood with patience, vigilance, and courage; but when tame &s;he never
&s;its well; and a common hen be|comes her &s;ub&s;titute; and for leading her
young to their food, &s;he is utterly ignorant where it is found&mdash;and the
young would &s;tarve if left &s;olely to her management&mdash;it is better left
at large in the woods than reduced to its pri&s;tine captivity&mdash;its
fecundity, when wild, is &s;ufficient to &s;tock the fo|re&s;t, and its fle&s;h
acquires a higher flavour from its <PB REF="439"> unlimited freedom&mdash;its
habits, when tame, v. 187&mdash;no birds are &s;hot more ea&s;ily, v.
188&mdash;when phy&s;i|cians of old &s;poke of whole&s;omne&s;s of viands, the
compari&s;on lay with the fle&s;h of the phea&s;ant, v. 186&mdash;the&s;e birds
taken young into keeping, be|come as familiar as chickens; and when de&s;igned
for breeding, they are put together in a yard, five hens to a cock&mdash;the
ne&s;t in their natural &s;tate&mdash;the female refu&s;ing to hatch the eggs,
a com|mon hen &s;upplies her place, and performs the ta&s;k with per&s;everance
and &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;the young diffi|cult to be reared, v. 188&mdash;with what
food the young mu&s;t be &s;upplied&mdash;particularities concerning the
rearing of the young ones&mdash;the method of Longo|lius, to encrea&s;e the
breed and make it more valu|able&mdash;the phea&s;ant will at la&s;t be brought
to couple with a common hen, v. 189&mdash;many varieties of phea&s;ants; of all
others, the <HI>golden phea&s;ant</HI> of China the mo&s;t beautiful, v.
190</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Phlegium,</HI> one of the highe&s;t mountains of
Ethiopia, &s;wallowed by an earthquake, i. 162</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pholas,</HI> the file-fi&s;h, places where the&s;e
animals are found, vii. 65, 69&mdash;their power of penetrating&mdash;the
pillars of the temple of Serapis at Puteoli were penetrated by them&mdash;they
pierce the harde&s;t bodies with their tongue, vii. 67&mdash;their motion
&s;low beyond conception&mdash;have no other food but the &s;ea-water, vii.
68&mdash;are accounted a great deliaccy, vii. 69</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pichincha,</HI> a remarkable mountain, near Quito, in
South America, i. 151</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pie,</HI> in the cla&s;s of the pie-kind, few, except the
pi|geon, are of u&s;e to man; yet, to each other, no cla&s;s of birds &s;o
ingenious, active, and well-fitted for &s;ociety, v. 220&mdash;they live in
pairs, and their attachments are confined to each other&mdash;they build
ne&s;ts in trees or bu&s;hes; the male &s;hares in the labour of building, and
relieves his mate in the duties of incubation; and the young once ex|cluded,
both are equally active in making them <PB REF="440"> ample
provi&s;ion&mdash;general laws prevail, and a re|publican form of government is
e&s;tabli&s;hed among them&mdash;they watch for the general &s;afety of every
bird of the grove, v. 221&mdash;they are remarkable for in&s;tinct and capacity
for in&s;truction&mdash;in&s;tances of it&mdash;fetching and carrying untaught,
all this tribe are but too fond of&mdash;their pa&s;&s;ion for &s;hining things
and &s;uch toys as &s;ome of us put a value upon&mdash;rings found in the
ne&s;t of a tame magpie, v. 222&mdash;the few general characters in which they
all agree, v. 223</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sea-pie</HI> breeds in this country, and re&s;ides in its
mar&s;hy parts, vi. 29</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pigeons</HI> are ruminating birds, iii. 5&mdash;tho&s;e
that live in a wild &s;tate by no means &s;o fruitful as tho&s;e in our
pigeon-hou&s;es nearer home&mdash;the tame pigeon, and all its beautiful
varieties, owe their origin to one &s;pecies, the &s;tock-dove&mdash;colours of
the pigeon in a &s;tate of nature, v. 285, 286&mdash;the dove-hou&s;e pigeon
breeds every month, v. 286&mdash;the hatching of its eggs, v. 287&mdash;a full
explanation of the method of feeding their young from the crop, v. 288,
289&mdash;pigeons bred to a feather means a di&s;play of art by tho&s;e
per&s;ons who employ them&s;elves in rearing pigeons of different colours, ii.
248&mdash;various names of tame pigeons&mdash;attempts made to render
dome&s;tic the ring-dove, but hitherto fruitle&s;s, v. 293&mdash;the
turtle-dove a bird of pa&s;&s;age&mdash;a pair put in a cage, and one dying,
the other does not &s;ur|vive, v. 294&mdash;the pigeon called ocotzimtzcan is
one of the &s;plendid tenants of the Mexican fore&s;ts, v. 295&mdash;pigeons of
the dove-hou&s;e not &s;o faithful as the turtle-dove&mdash;two males quarrel
for the &s;ame mi&s;tre&s;s; and when the female admits the ad|dre&s;&s;es of a
new gallant, her old companion bears the contempt with marks of
di&s;plea&s;ure, ab&s;tains from her company, or when he approaches is &s;ure
to cha&s;ti&s;e her&mdash;in&s;tances of two males di&s;plea&s;ed with their
mates, who have made an exchange, and lived in harmony with their new
companions, v. 290, 291&mdash;near fifteen thou&s;and pigeons may in four years
be <PB REF="441"> produced from a &s;ingle pair&mdash;the &s;tock-dove &s;eldom
breeds above twice a year&mdash;have a &s;tronger attach|ment to their young
than tho&s;e who breed &s;o often&mdash;the pigeons called carriers u&s;ed to
convey letters, nor trained with as much care as formerly, when &s;ent from a
be&s;ieged city to tho&s;e coming to relieve it&mdash;in an hour and a half,
they perform a journey of forty miles&mdash;the only u&s;e now made of them is
to be let off at Tyburn, when the cart is drawn away, v. 292</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pigmy,</HI> exi&s;tence of a pigmy race of mankind
founded in error or in fable, ii. 251</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pigtail</HI> is the la&s;t of the baboons&mdash;Mr.
Buffon calls it maimon&mdash;its de&s;cription&mdash;is a native of Sumatra,
not well enduring the rigours of our climate, iv. 215</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pike,</HI> the de&s;cription of this fi&s;h, vi.
313&mdash;poets have called it the tyrant of the watery plain&mdash;in&s;tances
of their rapacity, vi. 345</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Pilchards,</HI> little differing from the
