340&mdash;the &s;able re&s;embling the martin found in this country; &s;oldiers
and exiled crimi|nals <PB REF="481"> hunt it, and furni&s;h annually numbers of
its &s;kins, iii. 375&mdash;enormous tu&s;ks found lodged in the &s;andy banks
of the rivers in this wa&s;te country, iv. 282</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sicily</HI> and Calabria taught the other kingdoms of
Eu|rope the &s;ilk-manufacture, viii. 50</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sighs,</HI> in what manner produced&mdash;when
invigorated produce &s;obbing, ii. 92</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sight,</HI> of old men indi&s;tinct for bodies clo&s;e to
them, but more preci&s;e for objects at a di&s;tance from them, and why, ii.
158&mdash;of birds exceeds that of other animals, and excels in &s;trength and
preci&s;ion&mdash;a kite, from an imperceptible height in the clouds, &s;ees
its prey, and darts on it with unerring aim, v. 10&mdash;of birds that prey by
day, a&s;toni&s;hingly quick; and in &s;uch as ravage by night, &s;o fitted as
to di&s;|cern objects in darkne&s;s with preci&s;ion, v. 80</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Signs of death,</HI> uncertainty of them ought to make
every one cautious of giving up a friend as dead, and expo&s;ing him to real
death, or a premature en|terment, ii. 208 to 210</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Silks,</HI> brought to Jamaica, and there expo&s;ed to
the air, rot while they pre&s;erve their colour, but kept from air retain their
&s;trength and glo&s;s, i. 314&mdash;anciently &s;o &s;carce in Rome as to be
&s;old for their weight in gold; and con&s;idered &s;uch a luxurious refinement
in dre&s;s, that infamy was attached to wearing &s;tuffs in which it made but
half the compo&s;ition, viii. 49</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Silk-worm,</HI> its real hi&s;tory unknown among the
Ro|mans to the time of Ju&s;tinian; and &s;uppo&s;ed only brought into Europe
in the twelfth century, viii. 50&mdash;two methods of breeding them, viii.
51&mdash;Pau&s;anias's de&s;cription of this worm, viii. 50&mdash;changes of
its &s;kin in three weeks or a month, viii. 55&mdash;gummy fluid forming the
threads, viii. 56&mdash;preparations made before &s;pinning the web, viii.
57&mdash;the cone or ball of &s;ilk de&s;cribed, viii. 58&mdash;efforts to
bur&s;t the cone&mdash;free from confine|ment, it neither flies nor eats; the
male &s;eeks the <PB REF="482"> female, impregnates her in an uninterrupted
union of four days, then dies upon reparation, the &s;ur|vives till &s;he has
laid her eggs, which are hatched into worms the en&s;uing &s;pring&mdash;few of
the&s;e ani|mals &s;uffered to come to a &s;tate of maturity, and why, viii.
59&mdash;the mo&s;t &s;erviceable of all &s;uch creatures, viii. 4</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Manufactures of &s;ilk,</HI> e&s;tabli&s;hed in Europe,
in the beginning of the twelfth century, by Roger of Si|cily, viii. 50</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Silurus,</HI> the &s;heat fi&s;h of the prickly-finned
abdominal kind, its de&s;cription, vi. 310</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Simeon,</HI> &s;aid to have lived an hundred and twelve
years, ii. 132</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sinews</HI> of the rein-deer, the &s;tronge&s;t kind of
&s;ewing thread, iii. 167</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Single,</HI> name of the tail of the &s;tag, iii.
113</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Si&s;kin,</HI> &s;inging bird of the &s;parrow-kind, with
thick and &s;hort bill, feeding on grain and fruit, v. 315&mdash;time of its
migration, v. 317</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Size</HI> of men varies con&s;iderably, ii. 108&mdash;the
human body often differs from it&s;elf, ii. 110&mdash;the &s;ame per&s;on
taller when he ri&s;es in the morning, than going to bed at night; &s;ometimes
the difference is an inch; this fir&s;t perceived in England by a re|cruiting
officer&mdash;in what manner, ii. 108&mdash;the cau&s;e of it, ii.
109&mdash;men are tall from five feet eight inches to &s;ix feet
high&mdash;middle &s;ize from five feet five to five feet eight, ii.
108&mdash;Maximin, the emperor, above nine foot in height, ii.
118&mdash;ap|proaching towards the north pole, the natives di|mini&s;h
proportionably; growing le&s;s and le&s;s in higher latitudes, ii.
217&mdash;cau&s;e of their difference&mdash;an ox, on the fertile plains of
India, grows four times as large as the le&s;&s;er animal of the &s;ame kind in
the Alps, ii. 237&mdash;of men in all ages, nearly the &s;ame as at
pre&s;ent&mdash;many corroborating proofs of this, ii. 265</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Skates,</HI> Laplanders make u&s;e of them upon the
&s;now, and how, ii. 215</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB REF="483"><HI>Skeleton</HI> of the bat in &s;ome
mea&s;ure re&s;embles that of man, iv. 135&mdash;&s;ome human lately
di&s;covered of enormous &s;ize five, or &s;ix feet beneath the &s;urface, on
the banks of the Ohio, not far from the river Miume, in America, iv. 282</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Skin,</HI> the only part of the body that age does not
harden&mdash;whence its wrinkles proceed, ii. 197&mdash;of the rein-deer, a
more valuable part of the ani|mal than any other&mdash;u&s;es of it, iii.
166&mdash;of the tiger, much valued all over the Ea&s;t, iii. 243&mdash;of the
black fox mo&s;t e&s;teemed, a &s;ingle &s;kin &s;elling for forty or fifty
crowns&mdash;the hair is &s;o di&s;po&s;ed, that it is impo&s;&s;ible to tell
which way the grain lies, iii. 333&mdash;mo&s;t valuable part of the martin's
&s;kin&mdash;twelve thou&s;and of the&s;e annually imported into England from
Hud&s;on's bay, and thirty thou|&s;and from Canada&mdash;mo&s;t worth when
taken in the beginning of winter, iii. 372&mdash;of all, that of the &s;able
mo&s;t coveted, and held in highe&s;t price&mdash;a &s;ingle &s;kin four inches
broad, is often &s;old for ten or fifteen pounds&mdash;the fur &s;urpa&s;&s;ing
all other in having no grain; whatever way rubbed, is equally &s;mooth and
unre&s;i&s;ting, iii. 373&mdash;a cer|tain number of the&s;e furni&s;hed every
year by con|demned exiles, and Ru&s;&s;ian &s;oldiers, &s;ent into Si|beria to
kill the animal, iii. 375&mdash;of the ondatra al&s;o very valuable, iv.
80&mdash;of the mole, Agricola &s;aw the fine&s;t and mo&s;t beautiful hats
that could be imagined, made of their &s;kins, iv. 98&mdash;of the hedge-hog,
converted to no u&s;e, except to muzzle calves, from &s;ucking, iv.
105&mdash;of the elephant, not covered with hair&mdash;that part covering the
head re&s;embles the bark of an old tree more than the &s;kin of an animal, iv.
265&mdash;of the rhinoceros, &s;o thick as to turn the edge of a &s;cymetar,
and re&s;i&s;t a mu&s;quet-ball, iv. 286&mdash;is naked, rough, knotty, and
lying upon the body in folds, after a very pe|culiar manner, iv. 285&mdash;of
the o&s;trich, what u&s;e the Arabians make of it, v. 61&mdash;of the great 
<PB REF="484"> Greenland whale, marbled white and yellow, vi. 194&mdash;of the
civet, &s;o &s;trongly &s;cented, a per&s;on &s;hut up with one in a clo&s;e
room cannot &s;upport the perfume, iii. 392, 393</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Skink,</HI> an animal called one of the pole-cats of
Ame|rica, iii. 380&mdash;the author thinks it Cate&s;by's Vir|ginia
pole-cat&mdash;its de&s;cription, iii. 381</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Skull-fi&s;h,</HI> name of the whale above two years old,
vi. 200</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Slatberg,</HI> in Ireland (in the lands of) there &s;tood
a declivity, and the earth of it was found &s;liding down the hill upon the
&s;ubjacent plain, i. 160</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sleep,</HI> with &s;ome lower animals, takes up the
greate&s;t part of their lives&mdash;man the only creature requir|ing &s;leep
from double motives, for the refre&s;hment of the mental, and of the bodily
frame, ii. 134&mdash;want of it produces madne&s;s, ii. 135&mdash;procured to
man with more difficulty than to other animals&mdash;in what manner &s;leep
fetters us for hours toge|ther, according to Rohault, ii. 136, 137&mdash;care
re|quired to regulate its quantity, and why, ii. 137, 138&mdash;bodily labour
demands a le&s;s quantity of it than mental&mdash;the famous Philip Barrettier
&s;lept twelve hours in the twenty-four, ii. 138&mdash;&s;leep to &s;ome an
agreeable period of exi&s;tence&mdash;que&s;tions treated in the &s;chools to
this purpo&s;e, ii. 139&mdash;numberle&s;s in&s;tances of per&s;ons who,
a&s;leep, performed many ordinary duties of their calling; and, with
ridi|culous indu&s;try, completed by night, what they failed doing by
day&mdash;remarkable in&s;tance related in the German Ephemerides, ii. 140,
141&mdash;ridiculous hi&s;tory of Arlotto, a friar, with a narrative of the
actions of his life, when a&s;leep, ii. 142, 143</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sloth,</HI> two different kinds of that animal, the air
and the unan, iv. 343&mdash;de&s;cribed, 344&mdash;both &s;eem the meane&s;t
and mo&s;t ill-formed of all animals that chew the cud&mdash;their
food&mdash;formed by nature to climb&mdash;they get up a tree with pain, but
utterly unable to de&s;cend&mdash;drop from the branches to the ground, iv. 
<PB REF="485"> 345&mdash;move with imperceptible &s;lowne&s;s, baiting by the
way, iv. 346&mdash;&s;trip a tree of its verdure in le&s;s than a fortnight,
afterwards devour the bark, and in a &s;hort time kill what might prove their
&s;upport, iv. 345&mdash;every &s;tep taken, &s;ends forth a plaintive
melancholy cry, which, from &s;ome re|&s;emblance to the human voice, excites a
di&s;plea&s;|ing pity, iv. 346&mdash;like birds, have but one vent for
propagation, excrement, and urine, iv. 347&mdash;they continue to live &s;ome
time after their nobler parts are wounded, or taken away&mdash;their note,
accord|ing to Kircher, an a&s;cending and de&s;cending hexa|chord, uttered only
by night&mdash;their look piteous, to move compa&s;&s;ion; accompanied with
tears, that di&s;&s;uade injuring &s;o wretched a being&mdash;one fa&s;tened by
its feet to a pole, &s;u&s;pended acro&s;s two beams, remained forty days
without meat, drink, or &s;leep, iv. 347,&mdash;an amazing in&s;tance of
&s;trength in the feet in&s;tanced, iv. 348</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Slot,</HI> term for the print of the hoof of the &s;tag,
iii. 113&mdash;to draw on the &s;lot, a phra&s;e among hunters, iii.
114.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Slow,</HI> name given by &s;ome to the blind-worm, vii.
222</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Smell,</HI> no &s;ub&s;tance now known in the world has a
&s;tronger, and more permanent &s;mell than mu&s;k, iii. 89&mdash;&s;trong
offen&s;ive &s;mell of foxes often the cau&s;e of their death, iii.
324&mdash;of the wea&s;el-kind, kept tame about the hou&s;es of the planters in
America, not very offen&s;ive, iii. 383&mdash;of the genett, not endured by
mice and rats, iii. 388&mdash;the mu&s;ky not properly a characteri&s;tic mark
of any kind of animal, iii. 32</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Smelling,</HI> the &s;en&s;e in which man is mo&s;t
inferior to other animals&mdash;it never offends them&mdash;&s;tronger in
nations ab&s;taining from animal food, than in Eu|ropeans, ii.
179&mdash;bramins of India have a power of &s;melling, equal to what is in
other creatures,&mdash;can &s;mell water they drink, to us quite
inodo|rous&mdash;negroes of the Antilles by &s;mell di&s;tingui&s;h 
<PB REF="486"> the foot&s;teps of a Frenchman from tho&s;e of a
ne|groe&mdash;in a &s;tate of nature u&s;eful, not in our
&s;itu|ation&mdash;gives often fal&s;e intelligence, ii. 180&mdash;na|tives of
different countries, or different natives of the &s;ame, differ widely in that
&s;en&s;e&mdash;in&s;tances of it, ii. 181&mdash;mixtures of bodies void of
odour pro|duce powerful &s;mells&mdash;mixtures of bodies &s;epa|rately
di&s;agreeable, give plea&s;ant aromatic &s;mells&mdash;a &s;light cold blunts
all &s;melling&mdash;incurable aver|&s;ions to &s;mells formerly agreeable,
retained from di&s;orders&mdash;&s;malle&s;t changes in man make great
al|terations in this &s;en&s;e&mdash;antipathies to animals, who&s;e pre&s;ence
is perceived by the &s;mell, ii. 282&mdash;delicacy of &s;melling in birds
in&s;tanced in ducks, v. 11</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Savours,</HI> mechanical manner of accounting for
dif|ference of favours, ii. 183</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Smile,</HI> Fielding a&s;&s;erts, a per&s;on with a
&s;teady glaver|ing &s;mile, never failed to prove him&s;elf a rogue, ii.
94</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Snail,</HI> &s;hell of the garden-&s;nail, in what manner
formed, vii. 3, et &s;eq.</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Sea-&s;nail,</HI> a cartilaginous fi&s;h, de&s;cribed,
vi. 288</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Garden-&s;nail,</HI> is &s;urpri&s;ingly fitted for the
life it is to live&mdash;organs of life, it po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es in common with
animals, vii. 19&mdash;and what peculiar to it&s;elf, vii. 20&mdash;every
&s;nail at once male and female; and while it impregnates another, is
impregnated in turn, vii. 21&mdash;coupling the&s;e animals&mdash;hide their
eggs in great numbers in the earth, with great &s;olicitude and indu&s;try,
vii. 22&mdash;the growth of them, vii. 23&mdash;po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ed of the power
of mending the &s;hell; and come to full growth, they cannot make a new
one&mdash;Swammerdam's experiment to this purpo&s;e, vii. 24&mdash;their food,
vii. 26&mdash;&s;alt de&s;troys them, &s;o does &s;oot&mdash;a tortoi&s;e in a
garden bani&s;hes them mo&s;t effectually, vii. 25&mdash;continue in a torpid
&s;tate during the &s;everity of winter&mdash;&s;o great their mul|tiplication
in &s;ome years, that gardeners imagine they bur&s;t from the earth&mdash;wet
&s;ea&s;ons favourable to their production, vii. 26&mdash;<HI>&s;ea &s;nail,
fre&s;h water</HI> <PB REF="487"> <HI>&s;nail,</HI> and <HI>land &s;nail,</HI>
vii. 27&mdash;common garden &s;nail compared with the fre&s;h water &s;nail,
and &s;ea &s;nail, vii. 28&mdash;fre&s;h water &s;nails vivaporous&mdash;bring
forth young alive, with &s;hells upon their backs&mdash;expe|riment made by
Swammerdam to this purpo&s;e&mdash;at all times of the year, fre&s;h water
&s;nails opened, are pregnant with eggs, or with living &s;nails, or with both
together, vii. 29, 30&mdash;&s;ea &s;nails found vi|viparous, others lay eggs,
vii. 30&mdash;manner in which the &s;ea &s;nails impregnate each
other&mdash;dif|ferent orifices or verges of &s;nails&mdash;the difference
between land and &s;ea &s;nails, vii. 31&mdash;of the tro|chus kind, have no
mouth&mdash;their trunk&mdash;are a|mong &s;nails, as the tiger, the eagle, or
the &s;hark, among bea&s;ts, birds, and fi&s;hes, vii. 33&mdash;food of all
&s;ea &s;nails lies at the bottom&mdash;of &s;ea &s;nails, that mo&s;t
frequently &s;wimming upon the &s;urface, who&s;e &s;hell is thinne&s;t, and
mo&s;t ea&s;ily pierced, is the nautilus, vii. 35&mdash;its de&s;cription, vii.
36&mdash;nothing &s;eemingly more impo&s;&s;ible, yet is more certain, than the
nautilus &s;ometimes quitting its &s;hell, and re|turning to it
again&mdash;peculiarity by which the nau|tilus is mo&s;t di&s;tingui&s;hed,
vii. 37</ITEM>
<ITEM><HI>Snake,</HI> continues for &s;everal months together
&s;ub|&s;i&s;ting upon a &s;ingle meal, ii. 125&mdash;&s;nakes de&s;troy mice,
iv. 73&mdash;the only animal in the fore&s;t adven|turing to oppo&s;e the
monkey&mdash;larger &s;nakes often winding up the trees where they re&s;ide,
